14. mundi ac terrarum, ‘of the universe and the globe’ The process by which ‘mundus' carne to have this meaning is curious. Originally it signified an order or outfit; thus ‘mundus muliebris' stands for a lady's toilet requisites in the discussions on the Oppian law (Livy 34. 7), and ‘habere in mundo’ means ‘to have in stock‘ in old writers. It therefore comes to mean the ordered universe justas κόσμοι does in Greek.
